 Rs 225-cr postal kitty for stock play

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, May 24: The government today cleared the long standing demand of the department of posts (DoP) to invest interest earned by postal life insurance schemes in the equity market.

 Senior DoP officials said the department may venture into the stock market with an initial amount of Rs 225 crore ? a portion of the interest earned from the life insurance schemes of post office. The department of post has taken this initiative with a view to earning better returns for its investors.

 The corpus of rural postal life insurance scheme and postal life insurance scheme stands at Rs 10,000 crore. Next year, the interest and premium of this corpus, excluding the outgo, is expected to be Rs 1,500 crore. According to the norms stipulated by IRDA, 15 per cent of the Rs 1,500 crore can be invested in equities from the next financial year, said a senior DoP official.

 According to the IRDA norms, a majority of the interest income will go towards the government approved securities which will act as a safety cushion for the investors compared to the vagaries of the stock market. The returns from the market will go towards the Rs 10,000- crore corpus which will give bonus to the policy holders.

 Dayanidhi Maran, minister for information technology, today said DoP is working on this initiative. The finance ministry had set a time-frame of September 30 for the DoP to finalise this move but now the department had sought time till March 2007.

 as it is still busy preparing the groundwork for the entry into the stock market.




